content='The zoning rules and restrictions regarding residential real estate investments in Los Angeles, CA, particularly focusing on Accessory Dwelling Units (ADUs) and multi-family zones, include the following key points:\n\n1. **Density Requirements in R4 Zones**: In the "R4" Multiple Dwelling Zone, there is a minimum density requirement of one dwelling unit or guest room, inclusive of ADUs, for every 2,000 square feet of lot area. This applies to housing development projects that meet the minimum lot width and area specifications.\n\n2. **General ADU Regulations**: Los Angeles ordinances allow the construction of ADUs on nearly all residentially zoned lots, irrespective of their size. This regulation extends to multifamily properties, creating an opportunity for property owners to develop multiple ADUs on a single site.\n\n3. **Increased ADU Limits for Multifamily Properties**: Under the recent SB1211 regulation, multifamily properties can now accommodate up to eight detached ADUs, as long as this number does not exceed the existing units on the property. Previously, the cap was set at two new detached ADUs.\n\n4. **Regulations on Lot Sizes and Setbacks**: Local zoning laws dictate minimum lot requirements for ADUs, with variations across different zones. These laws also outline specific setbacks and land-use regulations that must be adhered to when constructing an ADU.\n\n5. **Definition of ADUs**: ADUs in Los Angeles are defined as units that contain full kitchen and bathroom facilities and are either attached to or detached from a primary residence. They are intended to provide independent living arrangements.\n\n6. **Expansion on Conversion ADUs**: Properties can add new detached ADUs as well as conversion ADUs, which refers to the adaptation of existing buildings. The maximum number of conversion ADUs allowed cannot exceed 25% of the original number of residential units on the property.\n\nThese zoning rules and restrictions provide insight into the opportu